{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"name":"ir","display_name":"R","language":"R"},"language_info":{"name":"R","codemirror_mode":"r","pygments_lexer":"r","mimetype":"text/x-r-source","file_extension":".r","version":"4.0.5"}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<h1 style=\"color: blue;\">Bellabeat Case Study with R</h1>\n\n![R_Programming.jpg](attachment:305b831f-8657-4504-97a5-1e93dccfdd9e.jpg)\n# <span style=\"color: blue; \"> Table of Contents </span>\n\n* [1. Bellabeat Case Introduction](#bellabeats_case_introduction_1)\n* [2. Ask Phase](#ask_phase_2)\n    * [2.1 Business Task](#business_task_2_1)\n* [3. Prepare Phase](#prepare_phase_3)\n    * [3.1 Data Collection](#data_collection_3_1)\n    * [3.2 Privacy and Accessibility](#privacy_and_accessibility_3_2)\n    * [3.3 Dataset Info](#dataset_info_3_3)\n    * [3.4 Data integrity and credibility](#data_integrity_and_credibility_3_4)\n* [4. Process Phase](#process_phase_4)\n    * [4.1 Installing Packages and Opening Libraries](#installing_packages_and_opening_libraries_4_1)\n    * [4.2 Importing datasets](#importing_datasets_4_2)\n    * [4.3 Preview](#preview_4_3)\n    * [4.4 Cleaning and Formatting](#cleaning_and_formatting_4_4)\n    * [4.5 Merging Datasets](#merging_datasets_4_5)\n* [5. Analyze and Share Phase](#analyze_phase_5)\n    * [5.1 Steps and Calories](#steps_and_calories_5_1)\n    * [5.2 User Types](#user_types_5_2)\n    * [5.3 Sleep and Time on Bed](#sleep_and_time_on_bed_5_3)\n    * [5.4 Daily and Hourly Steps](#daily_and_hourly_steps_5_4)\n    * [5.5 Usage Rate](#usage_rate_5_5)\n* [Act Phase](#act_phase)\n\n\n# <span style=\"color: blue; \"> 1. Bellabeast Case Introduction</span> <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"#bellabeats_case_introduction_1\"></a>\nBellabeat is a high-tech manufacturer in smart devices that focuses on improving and empowering womens health. Through innovative smart devices, Bellabeats can collect data about the user to give personalized and data driven advice for the user to utilize to improve their health.\n\nThis case has the following Stakeholders:\n*  Urška Sršen: Bellabeat’s cofounder and Chief Creative Officer\n*  Sando Mur: Mathematician and Bellabeat’s cofounder; key member of the Bellabeat executive team\n*  Bellabeat marketing analytics team\n\n# <span style=\"color: blue; \"> 2. Ask Phase</span> <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"ask_phase_2\"></a>\n### 2.1 Business Task <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"business_task_2_1\"></a> \nAs a new member of the marketing team, I have a task to uncover trends and make data driven decisions to drive our marketing operations forward. \n\n# <span style=\"color: blue; \"> 3. Prepare Phase</span> <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"prepare_phase_3\"></a>\n#### 3.1 Collecting Data: <a class=\"anchor\" id= \"collecting_data_3_1\"></a> \nThe data set \"FitBit Fitness Tracker Data\" is collected from Kaggle.\n\n#### 3.2 Privacy and Accessibility: <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"privacy_and_accessibility_3_2\"></a> \nThe dataset is publically available on Kaggle. Looking at the Meta Data, it is clear that every user has consented to their data being open-sourced.\n\n#### 3.3 Dataset info <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"dataset_info_3_3\"></a>\nThis dataset generated by respondents to a distributed survey via Amazon Mechanical Turk between 03.12.2016-05.12.2016. Thirty eligible Fitbit users consented to the submission of personal tracker data, including minute-level output for physical activity, heart rate, and sleep monitoring. Individual reports can be parsed by export session ID (column A) or timestamp (column B). Variation between output represents use of different types of Fitbit trackers and individual tracking behaviors / preferences\n\nFor this case we get 18 CSV files composing of quantitative data collected from Fitbit users. This data is in long format.\nSince the dataset is relatively small, using Pivot Tables can quickly identify the amount of users and days of usage respectively. \n\n| Table Name | Type | Description |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| dailyActivity_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Daily Activity over 31 days of 33 users. Tracking daily: Steps, Distance, Intensities, Calories |\n|dailyCalories_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Daily Calories over 31  days of 33 users |\n| dailyIntensities_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Daily Intensity over 31 days of 33 users. Measured in Minutes and Distance, dividing groups in 4 categories: Sedentary, Lightly Active, Fairly Active,Very Active |\n| dailySteps_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Daily Steps over 31 days of 33 users | \n| heartrate_seconds_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Exact day and time heartrate logs for just 7 users |\n| hourlyCalories_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Hourly Calories burned over 31 days of 33 users |\n| hourlyIntensities_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Hourly total and average intensity over 31 days of 33 users |\n| hourlySteps_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Hourly Steps over 31 days of 33 users |\n| minuteCaloriesNarrow_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Calories burned every minute over 31 days of 33 users (Every minute in single row)|\n| minuteCaloriesWide_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Calories burned every minute over 31 days of 33 users (Every minute in single column)|\n| minuteIntensitiesNarrow_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Intensity counted by minute over 31 days of 33 users (Every minute in single row) |\n| minuteIntensitiesWide_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Intensity counted by minute over 31 days of 33 users (Every minute in single column)|\n| minuteMETsNarrow_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Ratio of the energy you are using in a physical activity compared to the energy you would use at rest (Counted in minutes) |\n| minuteSleep_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Log Sleep by Minute for 24 users over 31 days. Value column not specified |\n| minuteStepsNarrow_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Steps tracked every minute over 31 days of 33 users (Every minute in single row)|\n| minuteStepsWide_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Steps tracked every minute over 31 days of 33 users (Every minute in single column) |\n| sleepDay_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV| Daily sleep logs, tracked by: Total count of sleeps a day, Total minutes, Total Time in Bed |\n| weightLogInfo_merged | Microsoft Excel CSV | Weight track by day in Kg and Pounds over 30 days. Calculation of BMI.5 users report weight manually 3 users not.In total there are 8 users |\n\n#### 3.4 Data Integrity and Credibility  <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"data_integrity_and_credibility_3_4\"></a>\nThis dataset has three main issues:\n\n* This Dataset is relatively small (30 users) which can result in sampling bias. \n* Demographic and geographic information is not disclosed.\n* This Dataset was collected hastily (2 months) and is not current as it was collected in 2016.\n\n# <span style=\"color: blue; \"> 4. Process Phase</span> <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"#process_phase_4\"></a>\n\n#### 4.1 Installing Packages and Opening Libraries  <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"installing_packages_and_opening_libraries_4_1\"></a>\nWe will be using following packages:\n\n* tidyverse\n* here\n* skimr\n* janitor\n* lubridate\n* ggrepel","metadata":{},"attachments":{"305b831f-8657-4504-97a5-1e93dccfdd9e.jpg":{"image/jpeg":""}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"library(tidyverse)\nlibrary(here)\nlibrary(skimr)\nlibrary(janitor)\nlibrary(lubridate)\nlibrary(ggrepel)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:14.323345Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:14.325743Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.599293Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### 4.2 Impoting Datasets  <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"importing_datasets_4_2\"></a>\nWe will be analyzing the following datasets to help our business task:\n\n* dailyActivity_merged\n* hourlySteps_merged\n* sleepDay_merged\n\nThe datasets with fewer than 33 users will be excluded.\n\n\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_activity <- read.csv(file=\"/kaggle/input/fitbit/Fitabase Data 4.12.16-5.12.16/dailyActivity_merged.csv\" )\nhourly_steps <- read.csv(file=\"/kaggle/input/fitbit/Fitabase Data 4.12.16-5.12.16/hourlySteps_merged.csv\")\ndaily_sleep <- read.csv(file=\"/kaggle/input/fitbit/Fitabase Data 4.12.16-5.12.16/sleepDay_merged.csv\")","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.601002Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.630065Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.719859Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### 4.3 Preview  <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"preview_4_3\"></a>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"head(daily_activity)\nstr(daily_activity)\n\n\nhead(hourly_steps)\nstr(hourly_steps)\n\nhead(daily_sleep)\nstr(daily_sleep)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.726509Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.727513Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.799330Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### 4.3 Cleaning and Formatting  <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"cleaning_and_formatting_4_3\"></a>\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"glimpse(daily_activity)\nn_unique(daily_activity$Id)\n\n\nglimpse(hourly_steps)\nn_unique(hourly_steps$Id)\n\nglimpse(daily_sleep)\nn_unique(daily_sleep$Id)\n","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.801101Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.802587Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.875449Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"All datasets fit into the range as intended.\nNow we want to see if there are any duplicates.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"sum(duplicated(daily_activity))\nsum(duplicated(daily_sleep))\nsum(duplicated(hourly_steps))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.877279Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.878232Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.922124Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"We can find 3 duplicates in the dataset daily sleep. Let's remove them!","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_sleep <- daily_sleep %>%\n  distinct() %>%\n  drop_na()","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.924848Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.926217Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.938450Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"We can now check if the duplicates has been removed","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"sum(duplicated(daily_sleep))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.946103Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.947237Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.963222Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Great! Now we want to check the formatting","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# activity\ndaily_activity$ActivityDate=as.POSIXct(daily_activity$ActivityDate, format=\"%m/%d/%Y\", tz=Sys.timezone())\ndaily_activity$date <- format(daily_activity$ActivityDate, format = \"%m/%d/%y\")\n# sleep\ndaily_sleep$SleepDay=as.POSIXct(daily_sleep$SleepDay, format=\"%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p\", tz=Sys.timezone())\ndaily_sleep$date <- format(daily_sleep$SleepDay, format = \"%m/%d/%y\")\n# step\nhourly_steps$ActivityHour=as.POSIXct(hourly_steps$ActivityHour, format=\"%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p\", tz=Sys.timezone())\nhourly_steps$date <- format(hourly_steps$ActivityHour, format = \"%m/%d/%y\")\n\nsummary(daily_activity)\nsummary(daily_sleep)\nsummary(hourly_steps)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.966121Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:15.967446Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:16.036422Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Now that that is finished, we can start merging datasets for further analysis. Looking at the summaries of each dataset, we can see that:\n\n* Average Total Steps is 7638 \n* Average Total Minutes Asleep is 419.2\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### 4.5 Merging Datasets  <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"merging_datasets_4_5\"></a>\nSince R is Case-sensitive when matching column names we can make it so every column name become lower case. This is to make sure we won't get any syntax errors.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"clean_names(daily_activity)\ndaily_activity<- rename_with(daily_activity, tolower)\nclean_names(daily_sleep)\ndaily_sleep <- rename_with(daily_sleep, tolower)\nclean_names(hourly_steps)\nhourly_steps <- rename_with(hourly_steps, tolower)\n","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:16.039170Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:16.040541Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:16.802917Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"To see if there is any correlation between daily actvity and daily sleep, we can merge the datasets for further analysis.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_activity_sleep <- merge(daily_activity, daily_sleep, by=c (\"id\", \"date\"))\nglimpse(daily_activity_sleep)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:16.805788Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:16.807358Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:16.867242Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"The activityhour is currently a date string. If we want to analyze the dataset it will be more convenient to make it into a date-time format","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"hourly_steps<- hourly_steps %>% \n  rename(date_time = activityhour) %>% \n  mutate(date_time = as.POSIXct(date_time,format =\"%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p\" , tz=Sys.timezone()))\n\nhead(hourly_steps)\n","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:16.870642Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:16.872446Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:16.918537Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"We also want to seperate the time and date in the hourly_step dataset so that we can analyze the time seperately in the future.\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"hourly_steps <- hourly_steps %>%\n  separate(date_time, into = c(\"date\", \"time\"), sep= \" \") %>%\n  mutate(date = ymd(date)) \n  \nhead(hourly_steps)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:16.921583Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:16.923217Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:17.652195Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# <span style=\"color: blue; \"> 5. Analyze and Share Phase</span> <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"#analyze_and_share_phase_5\"></a>\n#### 5.1 Steps and Calories  <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"steps_and_calories_5_1\"></a>\nFirstly we can see if there is a correlation between daily steps and daily calories burned.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(data=daily_activity, aes(x=totalsteps, y=calories)) + \n  geom_point() + geom_smooth() + labs(title=\"Total Steps - Calories\")","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:17.655463Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:17.657102Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:19.665483Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"As we can see, there is a clear correlation between how many steps you take and the amount of calories burned, which falls in line with our expectation.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### 5.2 User Types  <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"user_types_5_2\"></a>\nWe can classify the users we have by different types which we will determine looking at the daily amount of steps. Since we don't have any demographic information about the users, we can only classify them by using a general recommendation. \nFrom the following article: https://www.medicinenet.com/how_many_steps_a_day_is_considered_active/article.htm\nthe recommendation is:\n\n* Sedentary: Less than 5,000 steps daily\n* Low active: About 5,000 to 7,499 steps daily\n* Somewhat active: About 7,500 to 9,999 steps daily\n* Active: More than 10,000 steps daily\n* Highly active: More than 12,500 steps daily\n\nAnd now we want to calculate the average steps of our users.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_average <- daily_activity_sleep %>%\n  group_by(id) %>%\n  summarise (mean_daily_steps = mean(totalsteps), mean_daily_calories = mean(calories), mean_daily_sleep = mean(totalminutesasleep))\n\nhead(daily_average)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:19.667181Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:19.668045Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:19.742205Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"We can now use our mean values to classify our users into categories.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"user_type <- daily_average %>%\n  mutate(user_type = case_when(\n    mean_daily_steps < 5000 ~ \"sedentary\",\n    mean_daily_steps >= 5000 & mean_daily_steps < 7500 ~ \"lightly active\", \n    mean_daily_steps >= 7500 & mean_daily_steps < 10000 ~ \"fairly active\", \n    mean_daily_steps >= 10000 & mean_daily_steps < 12500 ~ \"active\",\n    mean_daily_steps >= 12500 ~ \"very active\"\n  ))\n\nhead(user_type)\n","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:19.745326Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:19.747041Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:19.780914Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"To make it more convienient to show on a graph, we can create a data frame with the percentage of each user types.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"user_type_percent <- user_type %>%\n  group_by(user_type) %>%\n  summarise(total = n()) %>%\n  mutate(totals = sum(total)) %>%\n  group_by(user_type) %>%\n  summarise(total_percent = total / totals) %>%\n  mutate(labels = scales::percent(total_percent))\n\nuser_type_percent$user_type <- factor(user_type_percent$user_type , levels = c(\"very active\",\"active\", \"fairly active\", \"lightly active\", \"sedentary\"))\n\nhead(user_type_percent)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:19.782585Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:19.783585Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:19.821249Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":"user_type_percent %>%\n  ggplot(aes(x=\"\",y=total_percent, fill=user_type)) +\n  geom_bar(stat = \"identity\", width = 1)+\n  coord_polar(\"y\", start=0)+\n  theme_linedraw()+\n  theme(axis.title.x= element_blank(),\n        axis.title.y = element_blank(),\n        panel.border = element_blank(), \n        panel.grid = element_blank(), \n        axis.ticks = element_blank(),\n        axis.text.x = element_blank(),\n        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=14, face = \"bold\")) +\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#006400\",\"#85e085\",\"#e6e600\",\"#FFA500\", \"#ff8080\")) +\n  geom_text(aes(label = labels),\n            position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5))+\n  labs(title=\"User types\")","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T03:22:19.060835Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T03:22:19.062674Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T03:22:19.370245Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### 5.3 Sleep and Time on Bed <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"sleep_and_time_on_bed_5_3\"></a>\nSecondly, we can check to see if the total minutes asleep and total time in bed falls in line with our expectation.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(data = daily_sleep, aes(x = totalminutesasleep, y = totaltimeinbed)) +\n  geom_point() +\n  geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, color = \"red\", linetype = \"dashed\") +\n  labs(title = \"Total Minutes Asleep - Total Time in Bed\")","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:20.293901Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:20.294901Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:20.644432Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"The red dotted line is y = x. Seeing as no point on the scatterplot is below the dotted line, we can conclude that the values make sense.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### 5.4 Daily and Hourly steps <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"daily_and_hourly_steps_5_4\"></a>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"hourly_steps %>%\n  group_by(time) %>%\n  summarize(average_steps = mean(steptotal)) %>%\n  ggplot() +\n  geom_col(mapping = aes(x=time, y = average_steps, fill = average_steps)) + \n  labs(title = \"Hourly steps (24h)\", x=\"\", y=\"\") + \n  scale_fill_gradient(low = \"red\", high = hcl(120, 100, 30))+\n  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:20.647468Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:20.649136Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:21.067867Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Analyzing the total steps throughout the day, we can see that most people start getting active around 08:00 and become more active in the afternoon and evening from 12:00 - 14:00 and 17:00 - 19:00.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### 5.4 Activity and Sleep <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"activity_and_sleep_5_4\"></a>\nLets analyze if there is a correlation between the amount you sleep and sedentary time.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(data=daily_activity_sleep, aes(x=totalminutesasleep, y=sedentaryminutes)) + \ngeom_point() + geom_smooth() +\n  labs(title=\"Minutes Asleep - Sedentary Minutes\")","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:21.070974Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:21.072625Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:21.619265Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"A negative relationship between the time you sleep and the time you are sedentary is made apparent. ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"#### 5.5 Usage Rate <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"usage_rate_5_5\"></a>\nFinally, we want to check the usage rate of our users. By knowing if our smart devices are frequently used or not, we can get insights into how to form our marketing strategy in the future.\n\nKnowing that our data has been collected in a span of 31 days, we can divide our analysis into three categories.\n\n* 1-10 days ~ low usage\n* 11-20 days ~ moderate usage\n* 21-31 days ~ high usage","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_use <- daily_activity_sleep %>%\n  group_by(id) %>%\n  summarize(days_used=sum(n())) %>%\n  mutate(usage = case_when(\n    days_used >= 1 & days_used <= 10 ~ \"low usage\",\n    days_used >= 11 & days_used <= 20 ~ \"moderate usage\", \n    days_used >= 21 & days_used <= 31 ~ \"high usage\", \n  ))\n  \nhead(daily_use)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:21.622231Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:21.624022Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:21.670808Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Lets create a data frame for visualization.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_use_percent <- daily_use %>%\n  group_by(usage) %>%\n  summarise(total = n()) %>%\n  mutate(totals = sum(total)) %>%\n  group_by(usage) %>%\n  summarise(total_percent = total / totals) %>%\nmutate(labels = scales::percent(total_percent))\n\ndaily_use_percent$usage <- factor(daily_use_percent$usage, levels = c(\"high usage\", \"moderate usage\", \"low usage\"))\n\nhead(daily_use_percent)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T02:24:21.675882Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T02:24:21.680207Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T02:24:21.737312Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Now we can create our plot.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily_use_percent %>%\n  ggplot(aes(x=\"\",y=total_percent, fill=usage)) +\n  geom_bar(stat = \"identity\", width = 1)+\n  coord_polar(\"y\", start=0)+\n  theme_linedraw()+\n  theme(axis.title.x= element_blank(),\n        axis.title.y = element_blank(),\n        panel.border = element_blank(), \n        panel.grid = element_blank(), \n        axis.ticks = element_blank(),\n        axis.text.x = element_blank(),\n        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=14, face = \"bold\")) +\n  geom_text(aes(label = labels),\n            position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5))+\n  scale_fill_manual(values = c(\"#004d99\",\"#3399ff\",\"#cce6ff\"),\n                    labels = c(\"High usage - 21 to 31 days\",\n                                 \"Moderate usage - 11 to 20 days\",\n                                 \"Low usage - 1 to 10 days\"))+\n  labs(title=\"Daily usage\")","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-09-30T04:19:03.384513Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-09-30T04:19:03.386111Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-09-30T04:19:03.682506Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# <span style=\"color: blue; \"> 6. Act Phase</span> <a class=\"anchor\" id=\"#act_phase_6\"></a>\nBellabeat focuses on empowering women by encouraging good health habits through their data discoveries. \n\nAs I have only been provided a small sample of Bellabeat's user base, it would be adviced that Bellabeat conducts further analysis on their own using their larger database. By knowing more information about their users like demographics, Bellabeats can continue to find trends to drive their marketing operations forward. \n\n![woman-female-legs-steps.jpg](attachment:16f44e4e-de93-42e8-a1a9-baf1017e85aa.jpg)\n\nFrom the small sample that I was able to work with, I have made following discoveries:\n\n* 20.9% of users make up the very active and lightly active category, which means 79.1% are either fairly active, lightly active or sedentary. \n* The average total minutes of sleep is 419.2 minutes\n* Activity of users start increasing around 08:00 and peaks from 12:00-14:00 and 17:00-19:00\n* 50% of users use our smart device frequently while the other 50% use it either moderately or not that often.\n\nWhich brings me to the following recommendations for the Bellabeat App:\n\n|Recommendation| Description |\n|---| ---|\n|1. Daily App Notifications| Since most of our user base is in the failry active, lightly active and sedentary categories with a average total daily steps of 7638,  I recommend to send frequent **daily notifications** to encourage our users to take the reccomended daily steps. According to a CDC research (https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2020/p0324-daily-step-count.html) taking 4000 steps daily is considered low for adults. **Taking 8000 steps a day is associated with a 51% lower risk for all-cause mortality while taking 12 000 is a 65% lower risk compared to taking 4000 steps a day**. |\n|2. In App Sleep Functions| In our analysis we found that the average total minutes our users sleep per day is 419.2,**which is less than the recommended amount**. We also discovered a negative relationship between total daily minutes of sleep and sedentary minutes. According to CDC research the recomended amount is 420 minutes (7 hours) for ages 13-18 and 480 minutes (8 hours) for people aged between 18-60 (https://www.cdc.gov/sleep/features/getting-enough-sleep.html). I recommend implementing new functions that let people set their own desired sleep cycle. The app can then **notify the user on when it is time to sleep** and inform what health benefits comes with sleeping the recommended amount. I also recommend developing a function to **monitor users' sleep cycles**, assess sleep quality, and offer potential solution. |\n|3. Reward system and Streak | By implementing a reward system and a streak function, we can potentially reach the users not motivated by notifications only. In this analysis we have categorised our users by the amount of steps they take a day. Incorporating this concept into our app involves introducing **monthly achievement levels**, such as Bronze, Silver, and Gold, which are determined by the number of steps users take within each month. The more steps a user takes during the month, the higher their achievement level becomes. Similarly, by having some quota each day for users to achieve, we can implement a streak function where the **streak depends on how many days in a row the user can achieve the quota**. This will not only motivate our users to take more daily steps, but also increase the usage rate of our products. |\n|4. Health Articles and Testimonies | To further promote a healthy lifestyle, we can enhance our app by introducing a **dedicated section featuring articles and user testimonials**. Here, users can explore a wide range of informative articles on wellness and gain insight from product users' health success stories. |\n\nTo make our products more wearable, we should also focus on developing smart devices that are durable, elegant and has long battery life. This ensures that our users can enjoy our products without concerns about appearance, battery life, or the need to remove them in harsh weather or while swimming.\n\n**Thank you for reading my case study in Bellabeat!**","metadata":{},"attachments":{"16f44e4e-de93-42e8-a1a9-baf1017e85aa.jpg":{"image/jpeg":""}}}]}